===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|wepen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|wēpan||to weep, complain, bewail, mourn over, deplore}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wōpijaną||to weep}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*weh₂b-||to call, cry, complain}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|wepe}}, {{m|sco|weip||to weep}}, {{cog|stq|wapia||to cry, complain}}, {{cog|is|æpa||to yell, shout}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|weeps|weeping|wept|past2=weeped}}

# To [[cry]]; [[shed tears]].
#* Longfellow
#*: They '''wept''' together in silence.
# To lament; to complain.
#* Bible, Numbers xi. 13
#*: They '''weep''' unto me, saying, Give us flesh, that we may eat.
# {{lb|en|medicine|of a|[[wound]] or [[sore]]}} To produce [[secretion]]s.
# To flow in drops; to run in drops.
#: ''a '''weeping''' spring, which discharges water slowly''
#* Shakespeare
#*: The blood '''weeps''' from my heart.
# To hang the branches, as if in sorrow; to be pendent; to droop; said of a plant or its branches.
# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To weep over; to bewail.
#* Prior
#*: Fair Venus '''wept''' the sad disaster / Of having lost her favorite dove.

